article.headline: Seattle 71, Houston 64
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson converted a three-point play with 1:26 remaining as the Seattle Storm snapped a five-game losing streak Saturday with a 71-64 victory over the Houston Comets. Seattle (17-16) avenged a 52-47 loss to Houston on Tuesday and improved to 12-4 at home, while Houston lost any chance of catching Los Angeles for first place in the Western Conference. The Comets dropped to 20-13 with one game remaining in the regular season. Jackson, the WNBA's leading scorer, put the Storm ahead 67-64 when she made a layup and was fouled by Tina Thompson. Jackson made the ensuing free throw, pushing the lead to 68-64. Janeth Arcane missed a jumper on the Comets' next possession, and Simone Edwards put Seattle ahead 70-64 on a layup with 35 seconds left. Houston was forced to foul, and Sue Bird made one of two free throws to complete the scoring. Jackson finished with 22 points -- 16 in the second half-- and eight rebounds. Edwards scored 14 points for Seattle, and Bird added 12. Thompson scored 18 points for the Comets. Seattle, which lost its seventh of 10, shot 47.5 percent from the floor. Houston shot 46 percent and outrebounded the Storm 32-21.

Game notes
Jackson scored 20 or more points for the 12th time this season. She has scored in double figures for 51 straight games, dating back to last season. ... Seattle's victory evened the season series at two games apiece, with each team winning twice at home.
